Introduction¶

About the Dataset¶

This data set includes information about individual rides made in a bike-sharing system covering the greater San Francisco Bay area.

The Data¶

Each trip is anonymized and includes:

  • Trip Duration (seconds)
  • Start Time and Date
  • End Time and Date
  • Start Station ID
  • Start Station Name
  • Start Station Latitude
  • Start Station Longitude
  • End Station ID
  • End Station Name
  • End Station Latitude
  • End Station Longitude
  • Bike ID
  • Bike share for all trip
  • User Type (Subscriber or Customer – “Subscriber” = Member or “Customer” = Casual)

This dataset will require some data wrangling in order to make it tidy for analysis. For this project, the data selected belongs to the month of April 2019. This data was selected because it had the least number of NULL entries and hence requires less time that will be spent during data wrangling as compared to other datasets available for different months. Some feature engineering will also be performed on the data to create new variables that will be used in the analysis and visualizations

Question Asked¶

  • What are the most popular and the least popular start and stop stations?
  • Which bike is most frequently used?
  • How many users are there in each catergory type?
  • What is the proportion of bike share for all trip?
  • Which day had most and least number of starting trips?
  • What is the most common hour of the day when the trips starts?

Addressing Issues¶

Issues

  • start_station_id, end_station_id and bike_id are not string types
  • start_station_id, start_station_name, end_station_id, end_station_name have some null values
  • start_time and end_time is not a datetime object
  • user_type and bike_share_for_all_trip columns are not categorical types

Feature Engineering¶

For our project we'll extract the date, month and hour values from the start time and end time columns and store these values in new columns

In [26]:
# Adding Month,Date, Day and Hour Column from start_time and end_time columns 

df['start_month'] = df['start_time'].dt.month_name()
df['start_day'] = df['start_time'].dt.day_name()
df['start_date'] = df['start_time'].dt.day
df['start_hour'] = df['start_time'].dt.hour

df['end_month'] = df['end_time'].dt.month_name()
df['end_day'] = df['end_time'].dt.day_name()
df['end_date'] = df['end_time'].dt.day
df['end_hour'] = df['end_time'].dt.hour

We'll also create two more columns for duration in minutes and hours from the duration sec column

In [27]:
#divide the duration_min column by 60
df['duration_min'] = df.duration_sec/60
In [28]:
#divide the duration_min column by 60 
df['duration_hour'] = df.duration_min/60
In [29]:
#rounding duration hour to two decimal places and duration min to zero decimal places 
df = df.round({'duration_min': 0, 'duration_hour': 2})

plt.ylabel('No of trips')
plt.title('Total no of trips based on duration in hours')
plt.xscale('log');
plt.xticks(ticks,labels);

Conclusion

We get a more normally distributed histogram with a slight skew towards the right and we can see that there are two peaks present in the data with the first one being slightly less than 0.1 hours and the other one being slighlty more than 0.2 hours

sns.countplot(data = df, y = 'end_station_name',order = df_index[-10:], color = base_color );
plt.xlabel('Total number of trips')
plt.ylabel('Name of stop station')
plt.title('Top 10 least common stop stations');
x_labels = np.arange(0, 19, 2)
plt.xticks(x_labels, x_labels);

Conclusions

We can see from the above visualizations that the most common start and stop station is San Francisco Caltrain Station 2 with around 4800 start trips and around 7100 stop trips. Market St at 10th st and San Francisco Ferry Building are the second and third most common start and stop stations.

Meanwhile SF Test Station, 17th St at Santa Clara St, Delmas Ave at Virginia St were the least common start and stop stations with less than 10 rides for the month of April 2019.

           cmap = 'Pastel2_r', center = 0)

plt.show()

From the above plot we can see that there is a high positive or negative correlation between a few variables. These are as follows:-

High Positive Correlation

  • start station longitude vs end station longitude
  • start station latitude vs end station latitude

High Negative Correlation

  • start station latitude vs start station longitude
  • start station longitude vs end station latitude
  • end station longitude vs end station latitude

Let's create a pairwise grid plot for the above numeric variables. To reduce the computation time and for clarity of the plots, we are going to choose a sample of 1000

In [69]:
#create pairwise grid plot of 1000 samples
g = sns.PairGrid(data = df.sample(1000), vars = num_var)
g = g.map_diag(plt.hist, bins = 20); #plot histograms on the diagonal axis 
g.map_offdiag(plt.scatter); #scatter plot on off diagonal axis

Conclusions

From the above charts, we conclude that there is no linear relationship between any two variables. These variables are divided into segments either on the vertical or horizontal axis
